  "assets": [
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/core_explanation/1",
      "kind": "core_explanation",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "Canonical Transformations — Core Idea (one sentence)",
      "content": "A canonical transformation is a change of phase-space coordinates (q,p) → (Q,P) that preserves the form of Hamilton's equations — equivalently, one that preserves Poisson brackets.\n\n---",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 20,
        "endLine": 25
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/worked_example/WE-1",
      "kind": "worked_example",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "Identity transformation via F₂",
      "content": "### Example 1 — Identity transformation via F₂\nGenerating function F₂(q,p,P) = qP (type-2: old q, new P).\nRelations: Q = ∂F₂/∂P = q; p = ∂F₂/∂q = P.\nConclusion: Q=q, P=p — the identity is trivially canonical.\nConfirms: {Q,P}={q,p}=1 ✓",
      "localKey": "WE-1",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 34,
        "endLine": 57
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/worked_example/WE-2",
      "kind": "worked_example",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "Exchange transformation (q↔p swap)",
      "content": "### Example 2 — Exchange transformation (q↔p swap)\nF₁(q,Q) = qQ (type-1: old q, new Q).\nRelations: p = ∂F₁/∂q = Q; P = −∂F₁/∂Q = −q.\nNew Hamiltonian K(Q,P) = H(q,p) = H(Q,−P).\nSignificance: position and momentum play symmetric roles — the harmonic oscillator H=p²/2m+mω²q²/2 becomes K=Q²/2m+mω²P²/2 (same form, swapped names).",
      "localKey": "WE-2",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 34,
        "endLine": 57
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/worked_example/WE-3",
      "kind": "worked_example",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "Action-angle variables for harmonic oscillator",
      "content": "### Example 3 — Action-angle variables for harmonic oscillator\nOld: (x, p) with H = p²/2m + mω²x²/2.\nDefine I = E/ω (action), θ = ωt + θ₀ (angle).\nTransform: x = √(2I/mω) sin θ, p = √(2mωI) cos θ.\nNew Hamiltonian K = ωI — cyclic in θ → İ = 0 (action conserved), θ̇ = ω (uniform rotation).\nApplication: K=ωI makes equations of motion trivial; generalizes to integrable systems.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "WE-3",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 34,
        "endLine": 57
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/misconception/MC-CT-ANY-COORD-CHANGE",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "\"Any coordinate change is canonical.\"",
      "content": "| MC-CT-ANY-COORD-CHANGE | \"Any coordinate change is canonical.\" | \"I can transform to any variables I want.\" | Only transformations satisfying {Qᵢ,Pⱼ}=δᵢⱼ, {Qᵢ,Qⱼ}=0, {Pᵢ,Pⱼ}=0 are canonical; point transformations Q=Q(q,t) are canonical, but arbitrary (q,p)→(Q,P) mixing generally is not. |",
      "localKey": "MC-CT-ANY-COORD-CHANGE",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-CT-ANY-COORD-CHANGE"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 29,
        "endLine": 29
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/misconception/MC-CT-GENERATING-IS-POTENTIAL",
      "kind": "misconception",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "\"The generating function is like a potential energy.\"",
      "content": "| MC-CT-GENERATING-IS-POTENTIAL | \"The generating function is like a potential energy.\" | \"F just generates the new coordinates.\" | F is a bridge function relating old and new variables via partial derivatives; four types F₁–F₄ suit different boundary conditions; F has units of action (J·s), not energy. |",
      "localKey": "MC-CT-GENERATING-IS-POTENTIAL",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [
        "MC-CT-GENERATING-IS-POTENTIAL"
      ],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 30,
