    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/mastery_probe/MP-1",
      "kind": "mastery_probe",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "MP-1",
      "content": "**MP-1** (retrieval): State the condition on Poisson brackets for (Q,P) to be a canonical transformation of (q,p).  \n*Answer*: {Qᵢ,Pⱼ}_{q,p}=δᵢⱼ, {Qᵢ,Qⱼ}=0, {Pᵢ,Pⱼ}=0.",
      "localKey": "MP-1",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 71,
        "endLine": 90
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/mastery_probe/MP-2",
      "kind": "mastery_probe",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "MP-2",
      "content": "**MP-2** (apply): For F₁(q,Q)=qQ, find p and P in terms of q and Q. Is this canonical?  \n*Answer*: p=∂F₁/∂q=Q, P=−∂F₁/∂Q=−q. Check: {Q,P}_{q,p}={Q,−q}=−{Q,q}=−(−1)=1 ✓ Canonical.",
      "localKey": "MP-2",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 71,
        "endLine": 90
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/mastery_probe/MP-3",
      "kind": "mastery_probe",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "MP-3",
      "content": "**MP-3** (analyze): For the harmonic oscillator H=p²/2m+mω²x²/2, using action-angle variables, write the new Hamiltonian K(I,θ) and state the equations of motion.  \n*Answer*: K=ωI; θ̇=∂K/∂I=ω, İ=−∂K/∂θ=0.",
      "localKey": "MP-3",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 71,
        "endLine": 90
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/mastery_probe/MP-4",
      "kind": "mastery_probe",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "MP-4",
      "content": "**MP-4** (analyze-MC): A student says \"Q=2q, P=p/2 is canonical because it's just a scaling.\" Verify or refute.  \n*Answer*: {Q,P}={2q,p/2}=2·(1/2)·{q,p}=1·1=1 ✓ This scaling IS canonical (symplectic with unit determinant). Correct student's reasoning: must check {Q,P}, not just \"it looks like scaling.\"",
      "localKey": "MP-4",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 71,
        "endLine": 90
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/mastery_probe/MP-5",
      "kind": "mastery_probe",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "MP-5",
      "content": "**MP-5** (evaluate): Show that Hamilton's equations are preserved under a canonical transformation: if dQᵢ/dt=∂K/∂Pᵢ and dPᵢ/dt=−∂K/∂Qᵢ hold, what is K in terms of H and the generating function F₂?  \n*Answer*: K(Q,P,t)=H(q(Q,P),p(Q,P),t)+∂F₂/∂t. If F₂ has no explicit t-dependence, K=H expressed in new variables.\n\n---",
      "localKey": "MP-5",
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 71,
        "endLine": 90
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/adaptive_rule/1",
      "kind": "adaptive_rule",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "Adaptive-Teaching Rules",
      "content": "| Trigger | Response |\n|---------|----------|\n| Student computes {Q,P}≠1 for a claimed-canonical transform | Validate the computation; confirm non-canonicity; distinguish from non-symplectic coordinate changes |\n| Student inverts F₂ derivatives correctly but gets wrong K | Check whether ∂F₂/∂t term was dropped; ask \"does your generating function depend on time?\" |\n| Student asks \"why do we need four types?\" | Explain: each type suits different boundary conditions; F₁ for q,Q known; F₂ for q,P known (Legendre analog); connects to different physical parameterizations |\n| Student confuses symplectic matrix J with angular momentum J | Use script J for symplectic, bold **J** for angular momentum; flag the collision immediately |\n\n---",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 99,
        "endLine": 110
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/session_flow/1",
      "kind": "session_flow",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "Session-Flow Template",
      "content": "```\nOPEN   (5 min) : Retrieval — \"What does {f,H}=0 mean?\" linking from Poisson brackets\nCORE-1 (15 min): TA-1 + TA-2 (hook + notation + four generating functions)\nCORE-2 (20 min): TA-3 + TA-4 (derivation + MC diagnostic probe)\nCORE-3 (20 min): TA-5 (action-angle example, full derivation)\nDRILL  (10 min): TA-6 (four-type derivative relations from memory)\nPROBE  (15 min): TA-7 (MP-1..MP-5)\nCLOSE  (5 min) : \"Hamilton-Jacobi chooses F₂ to make K=0 everywhere — next session.\"\n```\n\n---",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
      "span": {
        "file": "docs/curriculum/blueprints/phys.mech.canonical-transformations.md",
        "startLine": 110,
        "endLine": 123
      }
    },
    {
      "assetId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations/teaching_note/1",
      "kind": "teaching_note",
      "conceptId": "phys.mech.canonical-transformations",
      "title": "Known Sticking Points",
      "content": "1. **Four generating functions**: Students conflate F₁–F₄; remedy — table with old/new variables and sign conventions posted visibly; F₂ is the most common in applications.\n2. **Symplectic condition**: The matrix form MᵀJM=J is abstract; always translate back to Poisson-bracket condition for concreteness.\n3. **Action-angle variables**: \"How did you know to define I=E/ω?\" — motivation is that adiabatic invariants are actions; preview the Hamilton-Jacobi connection.\n4. **New Hamiltonian**: K=H+∂F/∂t confuses students — emphasize K=H only when ∂F/∂t=0 (most textbook examples).\n\n---",
      "localKey": null,
      "language": "en",
      "refs": [],
